Hybridization in the Rocky Mountains

Problem Statement:

Climate change is altering ecosystems worldwide, driving shifts in species distributions and in turn, increasing interactions between closely related species. One consequence of these changes is the potential for increased hybridization. This study investigates the role of a warming climate in influencing hybridization frequency between the American Marten (Martes Americana) and the Pacific Marten (Martes caurina) in the Rocky Mountains. I will analyze data collected to conclude if yearly temperatures, or other factors could have an impact of hybridization between the species using generalized linear models.

Climate data was taken from various weather stations using the Climate R package, and species data was collected from https://www.researchgate.net/publication/381774135_Ecological_displacement_in_a_Rocky_Mountain_hybrid_zone_informs_management_of_North_American_martens_Martes#

Statistical analysis of increased temperature by year:

The following model displays that average yearly temperature is significantly positively correlated with year. Meaning that as the year increases, so does average yearly temperature.

 modt <- glm( formula = ave_temp_year ~ year, data  = dat) 
 summary(modt)

Distribution modeling:

Two generalized linear models were produced below to determine the best model to predict hybrid frequency based on other variables within the data. Step AIC was then used to determine the best formula

Below depicts the summary of model one, using average temperature and year to determine hybrid frequency: Anlysis of this data indicates that the average temperature variable has a statistically significant positive correlation with hybrid frequency.

mod1 <- glm(hybrid_count ~ ave_temp_year + year,
    data = dat,
    family = poisson)
summary(mod1)

Below displays the various model assumptions:

check_model(bestmod)

Summary:

Overall, the data collected on marten species lacked longitudinal and latitudinal data for most specimens results in almost 300 NULL entries in other columns of the data frame. I would suggest repeating these analyses on a data set that contains all longitudinal and latitudinal data for the best conclusion as to what variables are influencing hybridization in the Rockies. However, it can be concluded from the first model, that average yearly temperature does have a significant effect on the frequency of hybrids found within that year.
